07593nam a22010815i 9783110566574DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20172018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2017048833  a97831105665747 a10.1515/97831105665742doi  a(DE-B1597)488010  a(OCoLC)1013819695  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN1995b.P445 2018 7aSOC0520002bisacsh  aAP 509002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7579:00aPerturbatory Narration in Film :bNarratological Studies on Deception, Paradox and Empuzzlement /ced. by Sabine Schlickers, Vera Toro. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VI, 265 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarratologia : Contributions to Narrative Theory ,x1612-8427 ;v5900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tDisturbance and Perturbation in The Tracey Fragments -- tA Tire Driving Crazy: Perturbatory Narration in Quentin Dupieux’s Rubber -- t“I am a complex being”: Filmic Puzzles in Julio Medem’s Vacas and Tierra -- tNarrative Empuzzlement in Robert Lepage’s Possible Worlds -- tThe Intrafictional Power of Fiction: Betibú by Miguel Cohan -- tSplitting and Splintering of Reality in Jaco Van Dormael’s Mr. Nobody -- tSensory Representation, Perceptual Spaces, and Perturbatory Distribution of Information in Shane Carruth’s Upstream Color -- tComplex Narration in Film: Reflections on the Interplay of Deception, Distancing and Empuzzlement -- t“This is still a game, isn’t it?”: On the Confusing Inability to Decide Between the Fictionally Real and Virtual in David Cronenberg’s eXistenZ -- tDeceptive Continuity: Classical Editing and Nonlinear Narrative in Nicolas Roeg’s Bad Timing -- tTaking Split Personalities to the Next Level: Perturbatory Narration in Enemy -- tPerturbatory Spaces in David Lynch’s Inland Empire -- tPerturbatory Narration in Mexican Film: Juegos nocturnos/Nocturnal Games, El agujero negro del sol/The Black Hole of the Sun, and El incidente/The Incident -- tPerturbatory Revocation: The Subtractive Cinema of Lisandro Alonso, Bruno Dumont and Béla Tarr -- tAbout the authors -- tFilms cited -- tAuthors cited0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerturbatory narration is a heuristic concept, applicable both quantitatively and qualitatively to a specific type of complex narratives for which narratology has not yet found an appropriate classification. This new term refers to complex narrative strategies that produce intentionally disturbing effects such as surprise, confusion, doubt or disappointment - effects that interrupt or suspend immersion in the aesthetic reception process. The initial task, however, is to indicate what narrative conventions are, in fact, questioned, transgressed, or given new life by perturbatory narration. The key to our modeling lies in its combination of individual procedures of narrative strategies hitherto regarded as unrelated. Their interplay has not yet attracted scholarly attention. The essays in this volume present a wide range of contemporary films from Canada, the USA, Mexico, Argentina, Spain, France and Germany. The perturbatory narration concept enables to typify and systematize moments of disruption in fictional texts, combining narrative processes of deception, paradox and/or empuzzlement and to analyse these perturbing narrative strategies in very different filmic texts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIncongruity in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture playsxHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aPerturbatory narration.  adeception.  afilm narratology.  aparadox.1 aBrössel, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo